1.3 Introducing Demographic Pyramids

Demographic pyramids visualize population distribution by age and sex. These bar graphs divided down the center between male and female members of the population. Age groups on the y-axis and sex on the x-axis.

Population pyramid for a country with a young population has a pyramid-like shape.

Three key features of a demographic pyramid are:

  1. Age Groups: The pyramid is divided into horizontal bars, each representing an age group, often in five-year increments.

  2. Gender Representation: The left side of the pyramid typically represents males, and the right side represents females.

  3. Population Size: The length of the bars indicates the size of the population in each age group.

{ggplot2} allows us to create and customize these pyramids.

1.4 Using Population Pyramids in Epidemiology

Pyramids aid in understanding age and gender-specific vulnerability to different diseases.

Incidence of diseases like TB, HIV, and malaria varies with age, sex, and differs by regions.

These visualizations can inform surveillance programs about which age groups to target.

Demographic distribution also assists in data quality assessment for routine surveillance by comparing national data with global epidemiology checks for external consistency.

1.5 Conceptualizing Demographic Pyramids

A population pyramid is essentially two bar graphs merged on the y-axis.

Below is the female half of the pyramid, with axes flipped:

We can also think of a demographic pyramid as akin to a modified stacked bar chart, with the bars centered at the point of division between the male and female sections.

To get this effect in geom_col(), we will calculate a negative count for males to plot the bars on the left side of the axis.

1.8 Creating Aggregated Data Subset

To plot a demographic pyramid, we need an aggregated data subset with occurrences per age group and sex.

We will use {dplyr} verbs to get aggregated counts and percentages per age group and sex.

Remember: in our subset female totals will be positive, and male totals will be negative to display on opposite sides of the axis.


# Create new subset
______________ <- 
  hiv_cases %>% 
  
  # Count total cases by age group and gender
  group_by() %>%
  summarise() %>% 
  ungroup() %>%  
  
  # Create new columns for x-axis values on the plot
  mutate(
    # New column with axis values - convert male counts to negative
    axis_counts = ifelse(sex == "male", ______, _____),
    # New column for percentage axis values
    axis_percent = round(100 * (axis_counts / sum(total)), digits = 1))

1.10 Plot Customization

Customize your demographic pyramid for clarity and information

1.11 Axis Adjustments

Proper visualization of data often requires adjusting scales.

The initial graph shows an asymmetrical x-axis range due to varying case counts between genders.

Well start by rescaling the y-axis to ensure symmetry in the demographic pyramid.

This involves identifying maximum value from our pyramid_data.

# Save max count as an object
max_count <- _____________(pyramid_data$counts)
## Error: <text>:2:15: unexpected input
## 1: # Save max count as an object
## 2: max_count <- __
##                  ^

Our goal is a y-axis that is symmetrical around zero.

We will use the the absolute values of max count to set y-axis limits.

# Use previous graph
custom_axes <- demo_pyramid +
  scale_y_continuous(
    # Set limits to the larger absolute value for symmetry
    limits = c(__________ * c(-1,1)),
    # Use absolute values for axis labels for clarity
    labels = abs)

custom_axes
## Error: <text>:5:17: unexpected input
## 4:     # Set limits to the larger absolute value for symmetry
## 5:     limits = c(__
##                    ^

Equal axis limits on both sides ensures a symmetrical and accurate visual comparison, facilitating proper interpretation of the data. Axis labels are transformed to their absolute value, so that the male case counts no longer appear as negative numbers.

1.13 Enhance Color Scheme and Themes

The aesthetic appeal of a graph is crucial for engagement and clarity.

Adjusting the color scheme and theme can greatly enhance interpretability.

Lets apply some style adjustments to our demographic pyramid.

# Build upon the adjusted axes
custom_color_theme <- 
  custom_axes +
  # Specify colors for each category
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("female" = "__________",
               "male" = "__________"),
    # Label the legend appropriately
    labels = c("____________", 
               "____________")) +
  # Fine-tune theme elements for a cleaner look
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(colour = "__________"),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
    plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0, size = 11, face = "__________"))
